  "content": "# Legal Research Summary Prompt\n\nYou are tasked with conducting comprehensive legal research and producing a professional research summary that synthesizes findings on a specific legal question or topic. Your summary will serve as a critical resource for attorneys preparing arguments, evaluating case strategy, or understanding the applicable legal landscape.\n\n## Research Scope and Methodology\n\nBegin by clearly identifying the legal question or topic requiring research. Determine the relevant jurisdiction(s), applicable practice areas, and the time period for which the research should be current. Your research should encompass three primary categories of authority: statutory law, case law, and regulatory guidance. For each category, identify the most authoritative and relevant sources.\n\nWhen researching statutory provisions, locate the current version of applicable statutes, noting any recent amendments or pending legislative changes that may affect the analysis. For case law, prioritize binding precedent from the relevant jurisdiction, followed by persuasive authority from other jurisdictions if applicable. Include landmark cases that established foundational principles as well as recent decisions that reflect current judicial interpretation. When examining regulatory guidance, identify administrative rules, agency interpretations, advisory opinions, and enforcement actions that provide context for how statutes are applied in practice.\n\n## Analysis and Synthesis\n\nYour research summary must go beyond mere citation collection. Analyze how the various authorities interact and identify any tensions, conflicts, or evolving trends in the law. Distinguish between settled legal principles and areas of ongoing development or controversy. When multiple interpretations exist, present each viewpoint with supporting authority and evaluate the relative strength of each position.\n\nOrganize your findings thematically rather than by source type. For instance, if researching employment discrimination standards, you might organize sections around burden of proof, protected characteristics, available remedies, and procedural requirements\u2014with each section drawing from statutes, cases, and regulations as appropriate. This integrated approach provides attorneys with a more useful understanding of how the law operates in practice.\n\n## Document Structure and Presentation\n\nStructure your summary to maximize utility for legal professionals working under time constraints. Begin with an executive summary that distills the key findings and bottom-line conclusions in two to three paragraphs. This should answer the core research question directly and highlight any critical nuances or limitations.\n\nThe body of your summary should be organized into logical sections with clear headings. Each section should begin with a topic sentence that states the legal principle, followed by supporting authority and analysis. When citing cases, include not only the citation but also a brief explanation of the holding, the relevant facts that distinguish or align the case with the current matter, and the procedural posture if relevant to the analysis. For statutory provisions, quote the operative language when it is central to the analysis, and explain how courts or agencies have interpreted ambiguous terms.\n\nInclude a dedicated section addressing counterarguments or alternative interpretations. Attorneys must anticipate opposing counsel's positions, so your summary should identify the strongest arguments against your primary conclusions and evaluate their merit based on the available authority.\n\n## Citations and Verification\n\nAll legal authorities must be properly cited in Bluebook format with verified sources. Each citation should link to the authoritative version of the source, whether that is an official reporter, government website, or other reliable legal database. Verify that each source actually supports the proposition for which it is cited by confirming the specific language, holding, or provision referenced.\n\nWhen you encounter citations that cannot be verified or sources that are unavailable, note this limitation explicitly rather than including unverified information. If research reveals gaps in the available authority\u2014such as an issue of first impression or an area where courts are divided without clear guidance\u2014acknowledge these gaps as they are material to the attorney's strategic decision-making.\n\n## Practical Application and Strategic Considerations\n\nConclude your summary with a section on practical implications and strategic considerations. Based on the research findings, what are the strengths and weaknesses of potential legal arguments? Are there procedural considerations, such as statutes of limitations or jurisdictional requirements, that affect how the law applies? Are there recent developments, such as pending appeals or proposed regulatory changes, that could alter the legal landscape?\n\nYour summary should empower the attorney to make informed decisions about case strategy, settlement negotiations, or client counseling. The goal is not merely to report what the law says, but to provide actionable intelligence about how the law is likely to be applied to the specific question or matter at hand.\n\nThroughout your research and writing, maintain objectivity and intellectual rigor. Your role is to provide accurate, comprehensive information\u2014not to advocate for a particular outcome. Where the law is unclear or subject to reasonable debate, present the analysis in a balanced manner that allows the attorney to exercise professional judgment based on complete information.",
